summary.p: 309 fol. on parchment, Shelfmark: 1 (shelfmark in the old catalogue: 29791, repository no. 4/3/303); Qurʾānic Text: Q 1-Q 26:200, Q 27:10-Q 108:1, Q 111-Q 114:6; 16-17 lines per page; Dimensions: 182 x 123mm; Script styles: kūfī B.II (fol. 295-304), D.IV (fol. 3-fol.294, fol. 306-307, fol. 309), post-classical kūfī (fol. 1-2, fol. 305-308).

This codex consists of three parts: Part 1 (fol. 3-294, 306-307 & fol. 309): It is the major part of the codex, written in D.IV style kūfī script with black ink. From the beginning until folio 37 every page contains 16 lines, after fol. 38, 17 lines are written on every page. Surah titles and illuminated marks for cluster of five verses are in golden ink, in some titles floral illuminations are drawn. Red dots are used for the vocalisation. Part 1 contains 295 folios (of the 309 folios) of the codex. The first two folios and some folios from the end of the manuscript are missing. The last folio contains a colophon, while its twin folio is missing. The recto side of the last folio (fol. 309) is not readable very well and some lines have been written over (remnants of the original writing still being visible). Surah titles and illuminations on this page are readable, and there is little no doubt that this page belongs to the original manuscript, however, the colophon has apparently been added, written in a different ink and by a different scribe. Fol. 309 verso has colophon which attributes this codex to ʿAlī b. Abī Ṭālib, dated to the year 40 AH [ 660 AD].

Part 2 (fol. 295 - fol. 304) contains 10 folios. The script style is B.II written in black ink with 16 lines to the page, Surah titles being written with red ink, marks for cluster of ten verses and dots vocalisation are written in red. These folios are added to cover the missing part, but it does not cover all the missing section. These folios seem to be older than the part 1, based on the script and parchment observation.

Part 3 (fol. 1, fol. 2, fol. 305, fol. 308) contains only 4 folios, added perhaps by the person who has written the endowment (waqf) deed on the 1st page in 1775 (1189 AH). The colour of the ink used for the endowment deed and the ink used for these pages seem to be identical (scientific ink analysis is necessary to confirm this observation). It seems the person who wrote these pages to complete the missing parts of the manuscript, had superficial knowledge of kūfī script and seem to have tried to copy the script from the manuscript (with some parts like of Surah 108, 109 and 110 missing between fol. 308v and fol. 309r).

Murtazavi Library and Research Center (Qum/Karachi) in cooperation with the Library of the Holy Shrine of Imām ʿAlī and Corpus Coranicum has taken five parchment samples from this codex. They were carbondated by the laboratories of Oxford University and ETH Zurich. The publication of the results is in preparation.

The images shown in this catalogue entry are from the archives of Murtazavi Library and Research Center (Qum/Karachi). They were published in 2013, cf. Murtaza, Syed Hussain, al Quran al Karim attributed to Imam 'Ali b. abi Talib (Ms. no. 1, Library of the Holy Shrine of imam 'Ali, Najaf), 3 vols, Qum, Murtazavi Library/Karachi, Zahra Academy, 2013.
The following scholarly works deal with codex 1 of Imam ʿAlī Library in Naǧaf:
al-Ḥasānī Ḥusain Ǧihād, Fihris al-maṣāḥif al-maḫṭūṭa fī ḫizānati l-ʿataba al-ʿalawiyya al-muqaddasa, Naǧaf, 2014, p. 218;
Murtaza, Syed Hussain, al Quran al Karim attributed to Imam 'Ali b. abi Talib (Ms. no. 1, Library of the Holy Shrine of imam 'Ali, Najaf), 3 vols, Qum, Murtazavi Library/Karachi, Zahra Academy, 2013;

Kariminia, Morteza, “Bibliography of Quranic Muṣḥafs (14): "Muṣḥaf of Najaf Ashraf", Kufi Quran No. 1 attributed to Imam Ali (as) in Najaf Ashraf”, Ayeneh-ye- Pazhoohesh 32(189) (2021), pp. 119-162 [doi: 10.22081/jap.2021.71413];
Šahristānī, Sayyid ʿAlī, Muṣḥaf Amīr al-Muʾminīn ʿAlī ‘alaihi as-salām bain al-munzal wa-l-mufassar, Qum, Dār al-Burāq, 2017.

The three parts of the manuscripts contain the following script styles (1) fol. 3-fol.294, fol. 306/307, fol. 309: kūfī D.IV; (2) (fol. 295-fol. 304: kūfī B.II; (3) fol. 1-2, fol. 305 and fol. 308): post classical kūfī style probably written in 18th century to complete missing parts of the codex.
